# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bristol-cars
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The **24 Hours of Le Mans** (French: ***24 Heures du Mans***; French pronunciation: [vɛ̃t.katʁ‿œʁ dy mɑ̃]) is an endurance sports car race held annually near the city of Le Mans, France.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] First run in 1923, it is the oldest active endurance racing event in the world and is widely considered one of the world's most prestigious races.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is part of two informal "Triple Crown" series: the Triple Crown of Motorsport (with the F1 Monaco Grand Prix and the Indianapolis 500) and the Triple Crown of endurance racing (with the Florida-based 24 Hours of Daytona and 12 Hours of Sebring).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Unlike fixed-distance races whose winner is determined by minimum time, the 24 Hours of Le Mans is won by the car that covers the greatest distance in 24 hours.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The cars on this track are able to achieve speeds of 366 km/h (227 mph), and reached 407 km/h (253 mph) on the main straight in 1988 – instigating the addition of more chicanes to the track to reduce speed reached.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Racing teams must balance the demands of speed with the cars' ability to run for 24 hours without mechanical failure.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is organized by the Automobile Club de l'Ouest (ACO).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is held on the Circuit de la Sarthe, composed of closed public roads and dedicated sections of a racing track.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 24 Hours of Le Mans was often part of the World Sportscar Championship from 1953 until that series' final season in 1992.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, it was a part of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2012, the race has been a part of the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A 10-hour American version of the race, called Petit Le Mans, has been held annually since 1998.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The most recent running of the event, the 94th 24 Heures du Mans, ran from 13 to 14 June 2026.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Launched when Grand Prix motor racing was the dominant form of motorsport throughout Europe, Le Mans was designed to present a different test.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Instead of focusing on the ability of a car company to build the fastest machines, the 24 Hours of Le Mans would concentrate on the ability of manufacturers to build sporty yet reliable cars.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This encouraged innovation in producing reliable and fuel-efficient vehicles, because endurance racing requires cars that last and spend as little time in the pits as possible.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, the layout of the track required cars with better aerodynamics and stability at high speeds.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While this was shared with Grand Prix racing, few tracks in Europe had straights of a length comparable to the *Ligne droite des Hunaudières*, often referred to as Mulsanne Straight after the village it leads to.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The oil crisis in the early 1970s led organizers to adopt a fuel economy formula known as Group C that limited the amount of fuel each car was allowed.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it was later abandoned, fuel economy remains important as new fuel sources reduce the time spent during pit stops.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Such technological innovations have had a trickle-down effect and can be incorporated into consumer cars.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This has also led to faster and more exotic supercars as manufacturers seek to develop faster road cars in order to develop them into even faster GT cars.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 2000s, hybrid systems (flywheel, super-capacitor, battery coupled with both petrol and diesel) have been championed in the Le Mans prototype category as rules have been changed to their benefit and to further push efficiency.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is held in mid-June, near the summer solstice, meaning the shortest night and very hot conditions for drivers, particularly in closed vehicles with poor ventilation.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race begins in mid-afternoon and finishes the following day at the same hour the race started the previous day.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2025 race attracted 332,000 spectators.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Modern competitors often cover well over 5,000 km (3,110 mi).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The record is 2010's 5,410 km (3,360 mi), more than six times the length of the Indianapolis 500 (500 mi or 805 km), or about 18 times longer than a Formula One *Grand Prix*.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Drivers and their teams strive for speed and avoiding mechanical damage, as well as managing the cars' consumables – primarily fuel, tires, and braking materials.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It also tests endurance, with drivers frequently racing for over two hours before a relief driver can take over during a pit stop while eating and resting.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Current regulations mandate that three drivers share each competing vehicle, with individual limits of driving no more than 4 hours in a 6-hour period, and no more than 14 hours total.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Competing teams race in groups called "classes", or cars of similar specification, while competing simultaneously for outright placing amongst all classes.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally, the race showcased cars as they were sold to the general public, then called "Sports Cars", in contrast with the specialised racing cars used in Grand Prix motor racing.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Over time, the competing vehicles evolved away from their publicly available road car roots.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] These are further broken down into: Hypercar (LMH or LMDh), LMP2 and LMGT3 (GT cars).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race was part of the World Sportscar Championship every year from its inception in 1953 until its demise in 1992, except during the 1956, 1975–1979 and 1989–1990 seasons.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the race was part of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup, and since 2012 it has been part of the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, winning Le Mans is often considered to be more important than winning the championship itself.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is also known as a leg of the informal Triple Crown of Motorsport which links Formula One, IndyCar, and sports car racing to represent a career achievement for drivers.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Additionally, it is seen as a leg of the Triple Crown of endurance racing, which links the three largest sports car races together, with the 24 Hours of Daytona and 12 Hours of Sebring forming the other legs.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1998, an endurance race called "Petit Le Mans" has been held every year as a 10-hour American version of the Le Mans 24 Hours.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] From 1999 to 2013, Petit Le Mans was part of the American Le Mans Series along with the 12 Hours of Sebring.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2014, the IMSA SportsCar Championship (a merger of ALMS and the Rolex Sports Car Series) has held all four major American endurance classics, which teams can use to prepare for racing at Le Mans.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Each car was required to have at least two seats.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, recently cars only need to have space to accommodate a second seat in the cockpit rather than the seat itself.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Two doors are allowed; open-cockpit cars do not require doors.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2014, all cars in the premier LMP1 category must have a roof for safety; open-cockpit cars are only permitted in the slightly slower LMP2 category.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2017, all prototype cars—Hypercar or LMP2—must have closed cockpits.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although all cars compete at the same time, as of 2021, there are separate classes.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A prize is awarded to the winner of each class and the overall winner.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The number of classes has varied over the years, but there are now three: Hypercar, LMP2, and LMGT3.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Successor to the Le Mans Prototype 1 (LMP1) is the custom-built Hypercar (LMH or LMDh) class.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is the top class and debuted in 2021.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The new technical regulations are intended to prevent cost escalations while enabling greater variety in technical approaches and car aesthetics.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is followed by the LMP2 class where teams are obliged to run one of four approved chassis – ORECA, Ligier, Dallara, or Multimatic/Riley – mated with a standard 4.2-litre Gibson V8 engine.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] ORECA is the most commonly used LMP2 chassis.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] LMP1 teams are not subjected to chassis and engine restrictions.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Their extra power, lower weight, and more complex aerodynamics result in much quicker lap times; LMP1 cars also may use hybrid technology.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The next class is LMGT3, which are similar to production-based sports cars.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Concept cars intended to test new automotive technologies may participate in the race under the "Garage 56" banner.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Such entries are classified in the race results, though are not expected to be competitive as their sole focus is to demonstrate experimental features.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, there were no rules on the number of car drivers or how long they could drive.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although almost all teams used two drivers in the early decades, some Le Mans drivers such as Pierre Levegh and Eddie Hall attempted to run the race solo, hoping to save time by not having to change drivers.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Until the 1980s, there were teams in which only two drivers competed, but by the end of the decade, the rules were changed to stipulate that at least three drivers must drive each car.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] By the 1990s, due to the speeds of the cars and the strain it puts on drivers, additional rules to reduce driver fatigue mandated that drivers could not drive for over 240 minutes (over 4 hours) and that no one driver could run for over 840 minutes (14 hours) total.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With careful management of driver stints, this makes it possible to complete the race with only two drivers (as Jeroen Bleekemolen and Cooper MacNeil did in 2014), although the vast majority of teams still continue to use three drivers.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2017, the driving time rules were further changed.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] If necessary, officials may require a drive time limit of 80 minutes of consecutive time behind the wheel and a minimum 30-minute rest break.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The rule applies only if the air temperature is at least 32 °C (89.6 °F).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it has been a part of the World Sportscar Championship for most of its existence, the race has had different regulations for safety and competition reasons partly due to its length.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For many decades, cars had to run at least an hour into the race before they could refill fluids for the car, such as oil or coolant, except for fuel.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was an attempt by the ACO to help increase efficiency and reliability.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Those who could not last the first hour without replacing lost fluids risked disqualification.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another rule unique to Le Mans is that cars must be switched off while refueling in the pits.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Not only is this safer and less of a fire hazard, but it is also another test of reliability, demanding a guaranteed ability to restart many times under race conditions.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another element of this rule is that mechanics are not allowed to work on the car while it is being refuelled (other than helping a driver in or out of the car), which has led teams to adapt innovative ways to decrease the time of these lengthy pit stops.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Drivers can get out of the car and be replaced by another driver during refuelling.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Those rules are also applied in the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] There are various long-standing traditions at Le Mans, including the waving of the French tricolor to start the race.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is usually preceded by a fly-over featuring jets trailing blue, white, and red smoke.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A similar flag tradition is track marshals waving safety flags during the race's final lap, congratulating the winners and other finishers.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Le Mans was the venue for the first televised instance of a winning driver celebrating by spraying champagne instead of drinking it.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When Dan Gurney won the 1967 race with co-driver A.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Foyt, the two drivers mounted the victory podium, and Gurney was handed a magnum of champagne.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Looking down, he saw Ford CEO Henry Ford II, team owner Carroll Shelby and their wives, as well as several journalists who had predicted disaster for the high-profile duo.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Gurney shook the bottle and sprayed everyone nearby.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Gurney autographed and gave the bottle of champagne to *Life* photographer Flip Schulke, who used it as a lamp for years before returning it to Gurney.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race has been cancelled ten times: in 1936 (a labour strike during the Great Depression) and between 1940 and 1948 (World War II).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race usually takes place on the second weekend of June, with qualifying and practice taking place on the Wednesday and Thursday before the race, following a car inspection on Monday and Tuesday.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Currently, these sessions are held in the evening, with two separate two-hour sessions held each night.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Friday serves as a day of rest, and a parade of all the drivers through Le Mans is held.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Test days held at the end of April or beginning of May served as a pre-qualification weeding out the slowest cars.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, in 2005 the exorbitant cost of transporting cars to and from Le Mans led organizers to move the test day to the first weekend of June.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Pre-qualification was eliminated in 2000, meaning that all competitors invited to the test would be allowed into the race.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2001 the Le Mans Legend races have mostly been part of the schedule, usually running exhibition races during qualifying days, a few hours prior to the sessions for the Le Mans entrants.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since its inception, the race has usually started at 4:00 p.m. local time (Central European Summer Time, UTC + 02:00) on Saturday.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, the car that covered the greatest distance from its starting position was the winner.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is known to have caught out the Ford team in 1966.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With a dominant 1–2 lead, the two cars slowed to allow for a photo opportunity at the finish line, with Ken Miles slightly ahead of Bruce McLaren.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, since McLaren's car had started much farther back on the grid than Miles's, McLaren's car had covered the greatest distance over the 24 hours.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With the margin of victory determined to be eight metres, McLaren and his co-driver, Chris Amon, were declared the winners.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The decision cost Miles and Denny Hulme a victory.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Miles had already won the other two endurance races at Sebring and Daytona.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With a win at Le Mans, he would have become the first man to win all three and the first to win them all in the same year.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The "greatest distance" rule was modified with the introduction of a rolling start in 1971.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Now, the car that completes the greatest distance as of the final lap's completion – where "greatest distance" is measured by the start/finish line for all competitors – wins.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When two cars finish the same number of laps, their finishing order is determined by the faster overall completion time.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This rule was used in the 2011 24 Hours of Le Mans to determine the race winner.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The top two finishers completed 355 laps, with only 13 seconds difference between them.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although "greatest distance run" determines the provisional order of finishers, additional requirements must be met for a car to be classified.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] All classification requirements hold except in exceptional circumstances, as determined by the race stewards.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race traditionally began with what became known as the *Le Mans start*, in which cars were lined up along the length of the pits.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Until 1962, cars lined up by engine capacity.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Beginning in 1963, qualifying times determined the lineup.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The starting drivers stood on the opposite side of the front stretch.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When the French flag dropped to signify the start, the drivers ran across the track, entered and started their cars without assistance, and drove away.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This became a safety issue in the late 1960s when some drivers ignored their safety harnesses, then a recent invention.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This led to drivers running the first few laps either improperly harnessed due to attempting to do it while driving or sometimes not even harnessed at all, leading to several deaths when cars were involved in accidents due to the bunched field at the start.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This starting method inspired Porsche to locate the ignition key switch to the left of the steering wheel.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In a left-hand drive car, this allowed the driver to use his left hand to start the engine and his right hand to put the transmission into gear, which in turn shaves off a few tenths of a second.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Stirling Moss developed another method for speeding up the start.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] His car was waiting with first gear already engaged.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] He switched the starter on when he jumped in without depressing the clutch.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The starter motor immediately jerked the car forward, but the engine did not start due to low RPM.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After a few seconds of motion, he pushed the clutch down, allowing the engine to speed up and start while the car was moving.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Feeling the Le Mans Start was unsafe, in the 1969 race, Jacky Ickx opposed it by walking across the track while his competitors ran.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although he was nearly hit by a faster competitor's car while walking, Ickx took the time to fasten his safety belts before pulling away.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Privateer John Woolfe died in an accident on the first lap of that race; Ickx won.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The traditional Le Mans start was changed for 1970.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cars were still lined up along the pit wall, but the drivers were already inside and strapped in.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the dropping of the French tricolor, the drivers started their engines and drove away.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1971, a rolling start (sometimes known as an *Indianapolis start*) begins the race.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While the cars do still start out lined up against the pit wall, when the green flag is waved the cars pull away one by one to begin a formation lap behind the safety car; when that car returns to the pit lane, the starter waves the French flag to start the race.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The circuit on which the 24 Hours of Le Mans is run is named the Circuit de la Sarthe, after the department that Le Mans is within.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It consists of both permanent track and public roads temporarily closed for the race.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1923, the track has been extensively modified, mostly for safety reasons, and now is 13.626 km (8.467 mi) in length.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it initially entered the town of Le Mans, the track was cut short to better protect spectators.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This led to the creation of the Dunlop Curve and Tertre Rouge corners before rejoining the old circuit on the Mulsanne Straight.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another major change was on the Mulsanne itself in 1990 when the FIA decreed that it would no longer sanction any circuit that had a straight longer than 2 km (1.2 mi).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] To comply with this, two chicanes were added to the 6-kilometre-long (3.7 mi) straight, dividing it into three pieces about 2 km each.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The addition of the chicanes was further influenced by the fact that the speed of Welter Racing's WM P88, driven by French driver Roger Dorchy, had been timed at 407 km/h (253 mph) during the 1988 race.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was the record speed before the addition of the chicanes.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Due to the shorter length of the straights, the speed record at Le Mans now, after the introduction of the chicanes, is 366 km/h (227 mph).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Typically race cars achieve top speed of just under 320 km/h (200 mph) at the current track (with chicanes).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The public sections of the track differ from the permanent circuit, especially in comparison with the Bugatti Circuit which is inside the Circuit de la Sarthe.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Due to heavy traffic, the public roads are not as smooth or well kept.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] They also offer less grip because of the lack of soft-tyre rubber laid down from racing cars, though this only affects the first few laps of the race.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The roads are closed only within a few hours of the practice sessions and the race before being opened again almost as soon as the race is finished.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Workers have to assemble and dismantle safety barriers every year for the public sections.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 24 Hours of Le Mans was first run on 26 and 27 May 1923, through public roads around Le Mans.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally planned to be a three-year event, as part of the Rudge-Whitworth Triennial Cup, with a winner being declared by the car which could go the farthest distance over three consecutive 24-hour races, this idea was abandoned in 1928.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Overall winners were declared for every year depending on who covered the furthest distance by the time 24 hours were up.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The early races were dominated by French, British, and Italian drivers, teams, and cars, with Bugatti, Bentley, and Alfa Romeo being the top brands.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Innovations in car design began appearing at the track in the late 1930s, with Bugatti and Alfa Romeo running highly aerodynamic bodywork to run down the Mulsanne Straight at faster speeds.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race was cancelled in 1936 due to general strikes in France, and the outbreak of World War II in 1939 resulted in a ten-year hiatus.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Following the reconstruction of circuit facilities, the race was resumed in 1949 with renewed interest from major automobile manufacturers.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 1949 was also Ferrari's first victory, the 166MM of Luigi Chinetti and Peter Mitchell-Thomson.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After the formation of the World Sportscar Championship in 1953, of which Le Mans was a part, Ferrari, Aston Martin, Mercedes-Benz, Jaguar and many others began sending multiple cars backed by their respective factories to compete for overall wins against their competitors.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This competitiveness sometimes resulted in tragedy, as in the 1955 Le Mans disaster during the 1955 race in which Pierre Levegh's car crashed into a crowd of spectators, killing more than 80 people.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The incident led to the widespread introduction of safety measures, not only at the circuit but elsewhere in the motorsport world.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The entire pit complex was razed and rebuilt further back following the accident, allowing the pit straight to be widened.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, there was still no barrier between the track and the pit lane.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Safety standards improved, but the cars got faster.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The move from open-cockpit roadsters to closed-cockpit coupés resulted in speeds of over 320 km/h (200 mph) on the Mulsanne.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ford entered the picture with the GT40, finally ending Ferrari's dominance with four straight wins (1966–1969) before the 1960s ended and the cars and the race changed substantially.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In those years racing took a turn towards more extreme speeds and automotive designs.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This contributed to the replacement of the typical standing *Le Mans start* with a rolling *Indianapolis start*.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Purpose-built sportscars became the norm, with the traditional production-based cars now racing in lower classes.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche was dominant throughout the decade with their 917, 935, and 936 models.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] French manufacturers Matra-Simca and Renault also gained success, with the first victories for the nation since the 1950 race.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Notably, 1978 saw the first win of a turbocharged engine with the Renault Alpine A443.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The decade is also remembered for strong performances from many privateer constructors, with two scoring the only victories for a privateer in the decade.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] John Wyer's Mirage won in 1975, while Jean Rondeau's self-titled chassis took 1980.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The rest of the 1980s was known for the dominance by Porsche under the new Group C race car formula that encouraged fuel efficiency.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally running the effective 956, it was later replaced by the 962.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Both chassis were affordable enough for privateers to purchase them en masse, leading to the two model types winning six years in a row.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Jaguar and Mercedes-Benz returned to sports car racing, with Jaguar being the first to break Porsche's dominance with victories in 1988 and 1990 (with the XJR-9 and Jaguar XJR-12 respectively).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mercedes-Benz won in 1989, with what was seen as the latest incarnation of the elegant "Silver Arrows", the Sauber C9, while an influx of Japanese manufacturer interest saw prototypes from Nissan and Toyota.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In qualifying for the 1988 race, a WM Peugeot – built for speed, not meant to (and it did not) endure 24 hours – set the never surpassed speed trap record of 407 km/h (253 mph) in the *Ligne Droite des Hunaudières*, famous for its 6 km (3.7 mi) long straight.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mazda would be the first Japanese manufacturer to succeed, with their unique rotary-powered 787B winning in 1991.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 1992 and 1993, Peugeot dominated the race with its Peugeot 905 as the Group C formula and World Sportscar Championship were fading in participation.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The circuit would also undergo one of its most notable changes in 1990, when the 5 km long Mulsanne was modified to include two chicanes in order to stop speeds of more than 400 km/h (250 mph) from being reached again.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This began the ACO's trend to slow the cars on various portions of the track.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, speeds over 320 km/h (200 mph) are still regularly reached at various points on a lap.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Following the demise of the World Sportscar Championship, Le Mans saw a resurgence of production-based grand tourer cars.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Thanks to a loophole in the rules, Porsche succeeded in convincing the ACO that a Dauer 962 Le Mans supercar was a production car, allowing Porsche to race their Porsche 962 for one final time, dominating the field.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although the ACO attempted to close the loophole for 1995, newcomer McLaren would win the race in their supercar's first appearance thanks to the reliability of the BMW V12 powered F1 GTR, beating faster yet more trouble-prone prototypes.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The trend would continue through the 1990s as more exotic supercars were built in order to skirt the ACO's rules regarding production-based race cars, leading to Porsche, Mercedes-Benz, Toyota, Nissan, Panoz, and Lotus entering the GT categories.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This culminated in the 1999 event, in which these GT cars were faced with the Le Mans Prototypes of BMW, Audi, Toyota and Ferrari.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] BMW would survive with the victory, their first and only overall Le Mans win to date.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, Mercedes left sportscar racing indefinitely following three catastrophic though non-fatal crashes stemming from severe aerodynamic flaws with their CLR.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This strong manufacturer influence led the ACO to lend the Le Mans name to a sports car series in the United States in 1999, known as the American Le Mans Series, which ran until the end of the 2013 season after which it merged with Grand-Am to form the United SportsCar Championship.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Many major automobile manufacturers withdrew from sports car racing after 1999 due to the high cost.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Only Cadillac and Audi remained, and Audi easily dominated with the R8.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cadillac pulled out three years later, and attempts by Panoz, Chrysler, and MG to beat Audi all fell short.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After three victories in a row, Audi provided engine, team staff, and drivers to Bentley, a corporate partner, which had returned in 2001.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2003, the factory Bentley Speed 8s beat privateer Audis.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The Chevrolet Corvette Racing Team and their C5-R won several times in the GTS class, finishing 1st and 2nd in 2001, 2002, and 2004.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] They finished 2nd and 3rd in 2003 behind Ferrari.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the end of 2005, after five overall victories for the R8, and six to its V8 turbo engine, Audi took on a new challenge by introducing a diesel engined prototype known as the R10 TDI.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although not the first diesel to race, it was the first to win at Le Mans.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This era saw other alternative fuel sources used, including bio-ethanol.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, Peugeot decided to follow Audi's lead and pursue a diesel entry in 2007 with their 908 HDi FAP.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 2008 race between the Audi R10 TDI and the Peugeot 908 HDi FAP, the Audi won by a margin of fewer than 10 minutes.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For the 2009 24 Hours of Le Mans, Peugeot introduced a new energy-recovery system similar to the KERS used in Formula One.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Aston Martin entered the LMP1 category, but still raced in GT1 with private teams.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi returned with the new R15 TDI, but Peugeot prevailed in its first overall win since 1993.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2010 running reaffirmed the race as a test of endurance and reliability.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Peugeot chose overall speed in adjusting their cars and engines to adhere to the 2010 regulations, while Audi chose reliability.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] All four Peugeots had retired at the end of the race, three due to engine failure, while Audi finished 1–2–3.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2011 and 2012 races were marred by a series of accidents.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the Audi driven by Allan McNish crashed heavily in the first hour, barrel rolling into a tire wall shortly after the Dunlop Bridge.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At night, the defending race-winning Audi driven by Mike Rockenfeller crashed similarly between the Mulsanne and Indianapolis corners.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Neither driver was seriously injured, nor were any spectators.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The third Audi entry was driven by Marcel Fässler, André Lotterer, and Benoît Tréluyer won the race.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2012 race saw two factory Toyotas replace Peugeot, which had withdrawn earlier, but one flipped at Mulsanne Corner.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Driver Anthony Davidson suffered two broken vertebrae but could exit the car himself.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Shortly after sunset, the other Toyota retired with mechanical difficulties, leading to another Audi victory.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the race became the premier round of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup, attempting to make a world championship for endurance racing again.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2012, the race became the centerpiece of the FIA World Endurance Championship, the successor to the ILMC.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2012 event was the first time the race was won by a hybrid electric vehicle, which was the Audi R18 e-tron quattro.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Regulations were changed for 2014, notably with a requirement that all LMP1 cars must be closed-cockpit, some changes to the hybrid system, and the introduction of the slow zone system.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche returned to Le Mans in 2014 with a new factory LMP1 program, and Nissan returned to run an LMP1 program in 2015.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi withdrew from racing at the 24 Hours of Le Mans in 2016 and Nissan after only one attempt in 2015.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche won the race in 2015, 2016, and 2017 with its hybrid 919, and remains the most successful manufacturer at Le Mans, with 19 overall victories.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2017, changes were made to the LMP2 regulations on cockpit and chassis, meaning all prototype cars must be closed-cockpit.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2018, Toyota won their first Le Mans with Fernando Alonso, Sébastien Buemi and Kazuki Nakajima driving.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2020 also saw the race held behind closed doors for the first time due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2021 saw the introduction of the Hypercar class, a class that allows for Le Mans Hypercars and from 2023 onwards also LMDh cars to participate.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2021 saw the race postponed once again, this time until August.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For 2021 and 2022, non-hybrid LMP1 cars were allowed to participate as "grandfathered" LMP1 cars, although only Alpine would make use of this.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Other entries in the hypercar class were Toyota and privateer team Glickenhaus.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The new Hypercar regulations allowed manufacturers more freedom with the design, leading to cars such as the wingless Peugeot 9X8 entering in 2022, with other unique designs expected to be added.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The LMP2 regulations were extended to 2027 with the next generation LMP2 cars to be introduced in 2028.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2028 will likely also see the introduction of hydrogen powered prototypes.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The former LMGTE class was also replaced by LMGT3 in 2024.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Le Mans has seen many innovations in automotive design to counteract the circuit's difficulties.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] These have either been dictated by rules or have been attempts by manufacturers to outwit the competition.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Some innovations were incorporated into the everyday automobile.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] One of the keys to Le Mans is top speed due to the long straights that dominate the circuit.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This has meant cars have attempted to achieve the maximum speeds possible instead of relying on downforce for the turns.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While early competitors' cars were street cars with their bodywork removed to reduce weight, innovators like Bugatti developed cars that saw the beginnings of aerodynamics.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Nicknamed *tanks* due to their similarity to military tanks in World War I, these cars used simple curves to cover all the car's mechanical elements and increase top speed.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Once Le Mans returned after World War II, most manufacturers would adopt closed bodies streamlined for better aerodynamics.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A notable example of the changes brought about by aerodynamics are the 1950 entries by Briggs Cunningham.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cunningham entered two 1950 Cadillac Coupe de Villes, one nearly stock and the other completely rebodied in a streamlined aluminum shape developed by Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation that looked so unusual that it was nicknamed "Le Monstre" by the French press.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The smoothing of body shapes and fairing-in of various parts of the machine brought about by the continual search for reduction of aerodynamic drag led to a separation from Grand Prix cars, which rarely had large bodywork.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] As the years went on, bodywork became all-enveloping, while at the same time lighter.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The larger bodywork with spoilers was able to provide more downforce for the turns without increasing the drag, allowing cars to maintain high speeds.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Extended bodywork would usually concentrate on the car's rear, usually being termed *long tail*.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The bodywork also began to cover the cockpit for less drag.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, open cockpits would come and go over the years as rules varied.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Aerodynamics reached its peak in 1989 before the Mulsanne Straight was modified.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] During the 1988 race, the crew of a Peugeot powered WM prototype taped over the engine openings, allowing Roger Dorchy to set a recorded speed of 407 km/h (253 mph) down the Mulsanne.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, the car was almost undrivable elsewhere on the circuit.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The engine was soon destroyed from a lack of cooling.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, for the 1989 event, the Mercedes-Benz C9 reached 400 km/h (249 mph) under qualifying conditions.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A wide variety of engines have competed at Le Mans in attempts to achieve greater speed and fuel economy and to spend less time in the pits.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Engine sizes have also varied greatly, with the smallest engines being a mere 569 cc (Simca Cinq) and the largest upwards of 8,000 cc (SRT Viper GTS-R).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Supercharging was an early innovation for increasing output, first being raced in 1929, while turbocharging first appeared in 1974.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The first entry without a piston engine came in 1963, when Rover partnered with British Racing Motors to run a gas turbine car with mixed success, an effort they repeated in 1965.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The American Howmet Corporation attempted to employ a turbine in 1968 with even less success: although the engines offered great power, they were hot and not fuel-efficient.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another non-piston engine that appeared was the Wankel engine, otherwise known as the rotary engine.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Used exclusively (in automotive applications) by Mazda since its introduction in 1970, the compact rotary engine suffered from fuel economy problems, yet eventually achieved the success that the turbines had not.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After many years of development, Mazda finally became the only winner of the race not to have a piston-powered engine, as it took the 1991 event with the 787B.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Alternative fuel sources have also played a part in more normal engine designs, with the first non-gasoline car appearing in 1949.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The Delettrez Special was powered by a diesel engine.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In contrast, a second diesel appeared in the form of the M.A.P. the following year.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although diesel was used on several occasions, it was not until 2006 that a prominent manufacturer, Audi, invested in diesel; the company's R10 TDI was a success.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ethanol fuel appeared in 1980 in a modified Porsche 911, leading to a class win.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Alternative biological fuel sources returned again in 2004 with Team Nasamax's DM139-Judd.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2008, biofuels (10% ethanol for petrol engines and biodiesel for diesel engines) were allowed.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi was the first to use next-generation 10% BTL biodiesel developed by Shell and manufactured from biomass.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Beginning in 2009, new regulations allowed hybrid vehicles with either KERS or TERS (Kinetic/Thermal Energy Recovery System) setups.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, only electrical (i.e., battery) energy storage was allowed, ruling out flywheel-based energy recovery.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cars with KERS were allowed to race in 2009 under specific classification rules.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2010, they have competed for points and the championship.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2012 the first KERS-equipped car won; the Audi R18 e-tron with a flywheel hybrid system by Williams Hybrid Power activated and drove the front wheels.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was only allowed in certain zones after the car had accelerated to at least 120 km/h to cancel out the acceleration advantage that all-wheel-drive cars could gain out of corners.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the same year, Toyota also started with a hybrid car, the TS030, which used KERS to power its rear wheels, meaning its usage was not restricted.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2025, the Automobile Club de l’Ouest is planning to introduce a hydrogen-electric prototype class.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This class will be a one-design class with a chassis provided by Red Bull Advanced Technologies-Oreca and a powertrain supplied by GreenGT.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The development of the hydrogen fuel cells powering the cars will be left to the teams themselves.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] According to the ACO's president Pierre Fillon, there is also a possibility of the cars being powered by a hydrogen combustion engine.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The performance of the class is expected to be competitive with the top Hypercar class.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Toyota unveiled new GR LH2 prototype for Gazoo Racing Europe.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With increased speeds around the track, brakes become a key issue for teams attempting to safely bring their cars down to a slow enough speed to make the Mulsanne Corner turn.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Disc brakes were first seen in 1953 when the Jaguar C-Type raced at Le Mans.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 1955 the Mercedes-Benz 300 SLR introduced the air brake using a large opening hood on the rear of the car.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ford used a quick change brake rotor in 1966 to achieve their first victory at Le Mans.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 1980s, anti-lock braking systems became standard on most Group C cars as a safety measure, making it less likely that cars lose control at high speeds.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] By the late 1990s, reinforced carbon-carbon brakes were adopted for better stopping power.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Over the years, many manufacturers have managed to take the overall win, while even more have taken class wins.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The most successful marque in the history of the race is Porsche, which has taken nineteen overall victories, including seven in a row from 1981 to 1987 and 107 class victories.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi is next with thirteen wins, and Ferrari follows with eleven, also including six in a row from 1960 to 1965.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2000 Audi has dominated the event, winning 13 times in 15 years of participation.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi and Team Joest have had two hat-tricks, the first being in 2000, 2001, and 2002.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In contrast, Toyota won five races in a row and Bentley, Alfa Romeo, and Ford all won four races in a row, with Bentley recording two additional victories in other years.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2018, Toyota became only the second Japanese marque to win, following Mazda in 1991.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mazda is also the only company to win with a rotary engine.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After Porsche's total of 107 class victories, Ferrari has 37, and Aston Martin, Audi, and Chevrolet each have 14.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Three drivers stand apart for their number of victories.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, Jacky Ickx held the record at six, scoring victories between 1969 and 1982, earning him honorary citizenship to the town of Le Mans.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] His frequent racing partner, Derek Bell, trailing by a single win, with five.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, Tom Kristensen has beaten this record with nine wins between 1997 and 2013, including six in a row.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Three-time winner Woolf Barnato (1928 to 1930), Tazio Nuvolari (1933), Luis Fontés (1935), American racing legend A.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Foyt (1967), Nico Hülkenberg (2015), and Fernando Alonso (2018–2019) are the only drivers to have won every Le Mans in which they participated.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Henri Pescarolo won the race four times, and holds the record for the most Le Mans appearances at 33.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Japan's Yojiro Terada was active as a driver until 2008, and holds the record for the most Le Mans starts without an overall win.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Claude Ballot-Léna holds the most class victories other than Kristensen with seven wins in GT class cars between 1970 and 1986.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Graham Hill is the only driver to win the so-called *Triple Crown of Motorsport*, winning the Indianapolis 500 (1966), Monaco Grand Prix (1963, 1964, 1965, 1968, 1969), and the 24 Hours of Le Mans (1972).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Le Mans has seen many fatal accidents due partly to the very high-speed nature of all variants of the track throughout history.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The largest one was in 1955 when at least 81 spectators (exact number unknown, many sources estimate 83) and driver Pierre Levegh were killed.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the wake of the disaster, many races were cancelled, including the Grand Prix races in Germany, Spain, France and Switzerland (the latter as a part of a blanket ban on motorsport round-track races that was maintained until 2022).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The accident led to safety regulations in all motorsports for both driver and spectator protection.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Almost all decades in which Le Mans has been run have seen many horrific accidents, such as in 1972 when Jo Bonnier was catapulted into a forest surrounding the circuit after hitting a privately entered Ferrari near the Indianapolis section; Bonnier was killed instantly.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 1980s was a decade where some of the race's worst-ever accidents occurred.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Although Armco barriers had been installed along the straight in 1969, there were still no chicanes on the Mulsanne Straight.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] It was here that almost all of the worst accidents occurred during that time.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1981, Belgian Thierry Boutsen crashed on the Mulsanne Straight in his WM-Peugeot, killing a marshal.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the same race, Frenchman Jean-Louis Lafosse was also killed on the Mulsanne Straight when his Rondeau suffered a suspension failure, steered very suddenly to the right, and slammed into the Armco barrier on the driver's side at extreme speeds.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 1984 race saw British privateer John Sheldon crashing at more than 320 km/h (200 mph) at the Mulsanne Kink; his Aston Martin V8 powered Nimrod tore through the Armco barriers into the trees.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The resulting explosion was so violent that the woods next to the track caught fire.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Although Sheldon survived with severe burns, a track marshal was killed; two others were also severely injured.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Sheldon's teammate, American Drake Olson in the second Nimrod-Aston Martin, who was following him down the straight, crashed heavily after running over Sheldon's bodywork; he went into severe shock but survived with minor injuries.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The field was under the safety car for over an hour while the crash site was cleared, and the destroyed Armco barriers were replaced.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1985, a similar accident befell Briton Dudley Wood in a Porsche 962 during practice.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The impact of the car against the Armco, considering Wood was doing more than 370 km/h (230 mph), was so hard that it cracked the engine block.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1985, John Nielsen flipped his Sauber-Mercedes while going over the Mulsanne hump at more than 350 km/h (220 mph).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The car landed on its roof and was destroyed, but Nielsen escaped without injury.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1986, Jo Gartner drove a Porsche 962C into the Mulsanne barriers and was killed instantly after the car rolled multiple times, vaulted some Armco barriers, and knocked down a telegraph pole.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Moreover, in 1987, American Price Cobb crashed a works Porsche 962C after slipping on oil during Wednesday practice.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The fuel tank exploded and the car burned to the ground, but Cobb escaped without injury.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Gartner's fatal accident remained the most recent death in the race until Allan Simonsen's crash in 2013.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, there was one fatality during a practice session in 1997 (Sebastien Enjolras).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1999, the Mercedes-Benz CLRs suffered from aerodynamic instability leading to cars getting airborne and flipping backwards, no less than three times.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] After initially happening on Thursday to the #4 car, Mercedes rebuilt the chassis on Friday and claimed to have solved the problem, only for it to occur again at warmup on Saturday.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Mark Webber was the unlucky driver whose car flipped on both occasions.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The last and most damaging accident occurred during the race itself when Peter Dumbreck's CLR #5 became airborne, flying over the safety fencing and landing in the woods several metres away.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] No drivers were severely hurt in any of the three accidents.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, Mercedes-Benz withdrew its remaining entry and ended its entire sportscar programme to focus on F1 and the upcoming new DTM.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2011, two horrific accidents occurred to two of the three factory Audis in the LMP1 class.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] 3 car driven by Allan McNish collided with one of the Ferrari GT cars, resulting in McNish's car smashing into the tyre wall and being thrown into the air at the Dunlop chicanes, resulting in pieces of bodywork flying over and nearly hitting many photographers on the other side of the barrier.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the eleventh hour of the race, another accident occurred to the No.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] 1 car driven by Mike Rockenfeller when he had contact with another Ferrari GT car.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the runup to Indianapolis corner, Rockenfeller's Audi was sent into the outside barrier at over 270 km/h (170 mph).
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Only the main cockpit safety cell of the car remained, along with major damage being done to the barriers that needed to be repaired before the race was resumed.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Audi had switched to a closed-cockpit car starting in 2011, a decision credited for the fact that neither driver was injured.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 2014 regulations required all cars to be closed-cockpit due to the 2011 accident.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2012, Anthony Davidson, driving for the returning Toyota team in a Toyota TS030 Hybrid, collided with a Ferrari 458 GT2 of Piergiuseppe Perazzini, and became airborne before crashing into the tyre barrier of the Mulsanne Corner at high speed.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The Ferrari also ended up in the barrier, flipping and coming to a halt on its roof.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2013, Allan Simonsen died after crashing into the barriers at Tertre Rouge.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] When the car collided with the guard rail, a mature tree had been touching the barrier, thereby preventing the guard rail from performing its safety function.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Motors TV covered the Le Mans 24 Hours in its entirety in 2006 and 2007, including coverage of the scrutineering, qualifying, driver parade, warmup, and race.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the United States, FOX owned SPEED Channel, followed by Fox Sports 1 and Fox Sports 2 aired complete race coverage live either on-air or online through a combination of coverage from the French host broadcaster and its own pit reporting crew for several years.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] A United States television deal was not done for the 2018–19 WEC Super Season because of a renegotiation of its European contract.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2008, Eurosport secured a multi-year deal to show the entire race, including the qualifying and the motorcycle race.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Every hour of the 2008 race was broadcast in segments on the main channel and Eurosport 2.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, a couple of hours were missed in recent years due to scheduling clashes with other sporting events.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In addition, Eurosport provided live streaming on its website to subscribers.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Since 2009, Eurosport and Eurosport 2 have covered all the action, and beginning in 2018, Eurosport gained United States broadcast rights for the World Endurance Championship for the race only on Motor Trend, a channel also owned by Eurosport's parent company.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Qualifying and practices aired on a direct-to-consumer streaming platform from Motor Trend magazine.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In Australia in 2012, Ten Sport showed the race live and in full online.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The race is also broadcast (in English) on the radio by Radio Le Mans.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Since 2001, the ACO has allowed the "Le Mans Legend" event to participate on the full Circuit de la Sarthe.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] These exhibition races involve classic cars that had previously run at Le Mans or are similar to those.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Each year, a particular era of cars may participate, with the featured era changing from year to year.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Though most drivers in this event are amateurs, some noted professional drivers have appeared to race cars they had previously run, such as Stirling Moss and Derek Bell.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Starting in 2002, the "Le Mans Classic" has been held as a biennial event on the full 13 km (8.1 mi) circuit in July.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The races take place over a full 24-hour day/night cycle, with starts on set times allowing cars from the same era to compete simultaneously.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] A team typically consists of a car in each class.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The team with the most points accumulated over five or six classes is declared the overall winner.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The classes are based on the era in which the cars would have competed.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The exact class requirements are re-evaluated for every event since the age for the youngest entries is shifted by two years for each event.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the first event, five classes ran more short races; later events have featured six classes running fewer but longer races.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Drivers are required to have an FIA International Competition license.
[src:bristol-cars/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] This event also includes a large Concours d'Elegance and auction.
[src:bristol-cars/abbey-automobile] The **Abbey** was a short-lived friction drive car assembled by the Abbey Auto Engineering Co.
[src:bristol-cars/abbey-automobile] It used a 10.8 hp 1498 cc Coventry-Simplex engine.
[src:bristol-cars/abbey-automobile] It was built in 1922 only and cost £315.
[src:bristol-cars/abbey-automobile] It also had Marles steering gear and friction drive.
[src:bristol-cars/abbey-automobile] After 1922 the car may have been sold as the Lewis.
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] The **ABC** was an English car manufactured between 1920 and 1929 by ABC Motors.
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] It was a light car (305 kg), powered by a 1198 cc flat-twin, air-cooled engine designed by Granville Bradshaw (the man who was also responsible for the ABC Motorcycle).
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] The engine however was difficult to start, loud, inefficiently lubricated, and prone to breakages, particularly the quite long, exposed push rods.
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] Over time quality improved dramatically.
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] Combined with the vehicle's light weight, the powerplant made the car quite fast for its size, capable of speeds approaching 60 miles per hour (97 km/h), and boasting quite good acceleration.
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] ABC was originally part of the Harper Bean combine, and was based in Hersham, Surrey and Harper Bean supplied castings, stampings, and forgings utilized on the first ABCs.
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] The car was expensive; in 1920 it sold for £414 but came down to £265 for a four seater in 1923.
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] The "radiator" cap was actually the fuel tank filler, which led to problems when mechanics unfamiliar with air-cooled cars topped off the fuel tank with water.
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] In 1925 a more refined version came featuring stronger valve gear, a better system of lubrication, and enclosed pushrods.
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] The company introduced a Super Sports model in 1925 with a 1320 cc engine.
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] This was the only model offered for the last four years of ABC's production.
[src:bristol-cars/abc-1920-automobile] Today the ABC is fairly rare and can be seen at shows and events around England.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The first car from the company that eventually became AC was presented at the Crystal Palace motor show in 1903; it was a 20 HP touring car and was displayed under the Weller name.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The Weller brothers of West Norwood, London, planned to produce an advanced 20 hp (15 kW) car.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] However, their financial backer and business manager John Portwine, a butcher, thought the car would be too expensive to produce and encouraged Weller to design and produce a little delivery three-wheeler.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1904, a new company was founded and named Autocars and Accessories; production started with the Auto-Carrier.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The vehicle caught on quickly and was a financial success.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Three years later, a passenger version appeared, called the A.C.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] It had a seat in place of the cargo box.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Sociable was described in a review of the 1912 Motor Cycle and Cycle Car Show as "one of the most popular cycle cars on the road, both for pleasure and business", and A.C. displayed eight vehicles on their stand, six for pleasure and two for business.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The single rear wheel contained a two-speed hub, and the single-cylinder engine was mounted just in front of it, with rear chain drive.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The company became Auto Carriers Ltd. in 1911 and moved to Ferry Works, Thames Ditton, Surrey — at this time, they also began using the famed "AC" roundel logo.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] They continued to produce the commercial 3-wheeler tricars and the A.C.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Sociable now frequently referred to in their adverts as the Mighty Atom.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Their first four-wheeled car was produced in 1913; it was a sporty two-seater with a gearbox on the rear axle.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Only a few were built before production was interrupted by the First World War.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] During the First World War, the Ferry Works factory produced shells and fuses for the war effort, although at least one vehicle was designed and built for the War Office.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] At the end of the war, Auto Carriers started making motor vehicles again, designing and building many successful cars at Ferry Works, as well as expanding into an old balloon factory on Thames Ditton High Street.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Shortly thereafter, John Weller started on the design of a new overhead-cam six-cylinder engine.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The first versions of this design were running by 1919.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The Weller engine would be produced until 1963.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1921, Selwyn Edge (who had previously been with Napier) bought shares in the company, and was subsequently appointed governing director.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] He did not get along with Weller or Portwine, who resigned less than a year later.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In customary fashion, Edge sought publicity for the company through motoring competition.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1921 Sammy Davis joined A.C. as a driver, competing in the Junior Car Club 200-mile (320 km) race, for cars up to 1,500cc, at Brooklands.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1922, the name changed again to AC Cars Ltd.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Joyce won the Brighton Speed Trials driving an AC.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In May 1924, at Montlhéry near Paris, T.G.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Gillett broke the continuous 24-hour record in a 2-litre AC, fitted with special streamlined bodywork, covering a distance of 1,949.3 miles.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1926, the Honourable Victor Bruce, an AC employee, won the Monte Carlo Rally in his 2-litre AC.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1927, Victor Bruce, with his wife Mildred (Mrs Victor Bruce), assisted by J.A.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Joyce, set a 10-day endurance record at Montlhéry, driving an AC Six.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Nevertheless, the sales started to fall.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Selwyn Edge bought the company outright for £135,000 in 1927 and re-registered it as AC (Acedes) Ltd., but sales, which had been falling, continued to decline.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The company was caught by the crash of 1929 and went into voluntary liquidation.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Production ceased for a time, and the company was sold to the Hurlock family who ran a successful haulage business.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] They wanted the High Street factory only as a warehouse (Ferry Works was not acquired), but allowed the service side of AC to continue.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] A single car was made for William Hurlock in 1930.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] He liked it and agreed to restart very limited production using components left over from previous models.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] An agreement was reached with Standard to supply new chassis, the ancient three-speed transaxle was replaced by a modern four-speed gearbox (built in unit with the engine), and by 1932 a new range of cars was launched.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Production continued on a small scale, averaging less than 100 vehicles per year, until the outbreak of the Second World War in 1939.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The final pre-war car was delivered in June 1940, after which the factory was fully involved with war production.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] After the war, AC secured a large contract with the government to produce the fibreglass-bodied, single seat, Thundersley Invacar Type 57 invalid carriages with Villiers 2-stroke engines.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The invalid carriages continued to be built until 1976 and were an important source of revenue for the company.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Production restarted in 1947 with the 2-Litre, using the 1991 cc engine from the 16.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The 2-Litre used an updated version of the pre-war, underslung chassis, fitted with the AC straight-six engine and traditional ash-framed and aluminium-panelled coachwork, available in saloon or convertible versions.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] They also built an aluminium-bodied three-wheeled microcar, the Petite, as well as "Bag Boy" golf carts (with independent suspension to the two wheels).
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1953, the firm began production of the AC Ace, based on a lightweight chassis designed by John Tojeiro and hand built aluminium body designed and built by Eric George Gray with the venerable Weller-designed 2-Litre engine.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] For 1954, a new aluminium-bodied closed coupe was unveiled at Earls Court, the AC Aceca, pronounced A-seek-a.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] It was only slightly heavier than the convertible Ace, and because of better aerodynamics was also slightly faster (128 mph (206 km/h) top speed).
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] There was a demand from some customers for a larger four-seater car, for whom AC produced the Greyhound.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] This was built on a stretched Ace chassis with coil suspension all around and a 2.2-litre Bristol engine.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In September 1961, AC was approached by Carroll Shelby to use a small block Ford Windsor V8 engine in the Ace chassis, producing the AC Cobra.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Shelby needed a car that could compete with the Chevrolet Corvette in US sports car racing.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Only a single example was built (CSX 2000) using a Ford 221 Windsor V8.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] It debuted in 1962 with a Ford 260 V8 engine.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] This was then superseded by the Ford 289 V8 engine.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1964 the company decided that in addition to supplying Shelby's chassis orders they would enter a works Cobra (which had the chassis number A98) in that year's Le Mans 24 Hours race.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] They contracted Jack Sears to be one of the drivers.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] To test its stability and gearing at the speeds the car was expected to reach in the race's three mile Mulsanne Straight they decided to test it beforehand along the only available place that was long enough to reach its potential top speed.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] This was the northern end of the first section of the six lane M1 motorway which had no barriered central reservation and no speed limit.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The use of the motorway for high speed testing was not unusual as Aston Martin, Jaguar and the Rootes Group had also used it.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] After Sears had some food at the Blue Boar service station and waited beside it for no traffic to pass for several minutes, he set off at about 4:15 am on 11 June 1964.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In top gear the car reached 6,500 rpm on its rev-counter (it had no speedometer) until the needle moved no more.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Sears then slowed down and returned to the engineers.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] From the engine revolutions and after compensating for tyre growth, they calculated that the car had reached 185mph.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Within days, after a conversation in a Fleet Street bar, reports of the high speed run made the headlines in national newspapers.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] This led to the Ministry of Transport investigating, but no action was taken as no laws had been broken.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Nine days after the M1 test, the car participated in the 1964 Le Mans race with Sears and Peter Bolton sharing the driving.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] While being driven in the evening by Bolton the car had a rear tyre blowout, spun and was then hit by the Ferrari of Giancarlo Baghetti.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Tragically the Cobra barrelled, speared off into the barriers and killed three young French spectators who were standing in a prohibited area.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Baghetti was uninjured but Bolton was taken to hospital with minor injuries.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The damaged Cobra was brought back from France and stored at the AC factory in Thames Ditton until in 1972 it came into the possession of collector Barrie Bird.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Over many years he undertook a full rebuild, including fitting it with new body manufactured by Maurice Gomm, who had created the car's original body.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] At the end of the 1964 racing season, the Cobra was being outclassed in sports car racing by Ferrari.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Carroll Shelby decided he needed a bigger engine.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] A big block Ford FE series 390 V8 was installed in a Cobra but it was over-powered and the car was now almost undrivable.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] It was decided that a completely new chassis was needed.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] With the combined help of Ford's computers and the experience of the AC engineers, the new MKIII was born with 4-inch (100 mm) main tubes instead of 3-inch (76 mm) ones for the chassis, adding huge cross-braced shock towers and coil springs all around.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1965 a competition version with a stripped interior, no glove box, different instrument layout and revised suspension was introduced.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The competition version also had a more powerful motor with only one carburettor, side exhausts, a roll bar and wider fenders to accommodate racing tires.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The engine that was installed in the car was Ford's famed 427 FE NASCAR "Side-Oiler" V8, a power-house engine developing 425 bhp (317 kW) in its mildest street version.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Unfortunately, the car missed homologation for the 1965 season and was not raced by the Shelby team.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] However, it was raced successfully by many privateers and went on to win races all the way into the 1970s.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] At the end of 1966, Shelby was left with 31 unsold competition cars; it was decided by Shelby American to sell them to the general public under the name of Cobra 427 S/C or Semi-Competition.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] These S/C cars have become the most sought after models and can sell in excess of 1.5 million dollars.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1966, a street model of the 427 S/C was made available.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] It came with a tamer motor, optional dual carburetors, a glove box, and exhaust running under the car.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Meanwhile, AC went on producing a milder version of the 427 MK III Cobra for the European market fitted with the small block Ford motor.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The car was called the AC 289 and 27 were produced.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Carroll Shelby sold the Cobra name to Ford in 1965 and went on to help develop the famed racing Ford GT40.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] At the same time, the company realized they needed a grand tourer model that could appeal to wealthy customers.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] AC contacted the famed Italian coach builder Pietro Frua to design an appealing GT body that could be fitted on a MKIII Cobra chassis stretched by 6 inches (150 mm).
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The new car was shown at the 1965 Turin show.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] A few early models were fitted with the famed 427 Ford FE motors.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1967 the long-stroked 428 motor became available and the car was known as the AC 428.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Built out of steel rather than AC's usual aluminium, the Frua is heavier than a Cobra at slightly under 3,000 lb (1,400 kg).
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] That said, it is still a light and very fast automobile built on a racing chassis.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The car was never fully developed and the cost of sending chassis from England to Italy and back for final assembly made it so expensive that only a few were produced.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Production ended in 1973 after only 80 cars (29 convertibles and 51 coupes) were finished.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1970, a special version of the coupé was built.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] It was based on an extended bodyshell that Frua built for Monteverdi which was supposed to become the second *Monteverdi 375/L* (Monteverdi chassis# 2002).
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] After the alliance between Monteverdi and Frua broke apart in Summer 1969, that bodyshell remained in the Frua works in Turin.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] A year or so later Frua changed some details on front and rear, including some semi-hidden headlamps similar to those seen on the *Iso Lele* and the second series *Iso Grifo* before.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The car was called AC 429; it remained a one-off.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The 1970s were not a good period for luxury car manufacturers and Derek Hurlock went searching for a totally new, smaller car.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Mid-engined designs were in fashion at the time and in 1972 the Diablo, a prototype with an Austin Maxi engine and transaxle, was built by privateers Peter Bohanna and Robin Stables.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In much the same way as they had taken up the Tojeiro prototype and turned it into the Ace, AC acquired the rights and at the 1973 London Motor Show showed their own version, the mid-engined ME3000 with the 3.0-litre Ford Essex V6 engine installed transversely over a bespoke AC-designed gearbox.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Development was virtually complete in 1976 when new Type Approval regulations were introduced.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] A prototype failed the 30 mph (48 km/h) crash test, and the chassis had to be redesigned.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] On the second attempt, the car passed with flying colours.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] This was a huge achievement for a tiny firm — Vauxhall had to make several attempts before the contemporary Chevette passed.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] For AC, such delays meant that the first production cars (later renamed 3000ME) were not delivered until 1979, by which time they were in direct competition with the Lotus Esprit.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Although comfortable, brisk, nicely built and practical, the car's handling was heavily criticised by writers from *Car Magazine*, *Autocar* and *Motor*.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] AC's ambitions of selling 250 cars per year were a distant memory.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] After just 71 cars were sold, Hurlock called a halt to production as his health was suffering and the company was struggling in the teeth of a recession.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1984, production stopped at Thames Ditton and the car and the AC name were licensed to a new company registered as AC (Scotland) plc run by David McDonald in a new factory in Hillington, Glasgow.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Here, 30 cars were built, including a development car tested with Alfa Romeo's 2.5-litre V6 engine and a nearly complete Mark 2 prototype of the same.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Regardless (or possibly because) of these developments, AC Scotland called in the receivers in 1985.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] After selling the historic High Street works for redevelopment, AC themselves soldiered on as a service operation in the "21st Century" works on Summer Road until the Hurlock family finally sold their holdings in 1986 to William West.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] After some complex machinations, the company was split between property interests and the car brand; the former was renamed and the latter was acquired by C.P.Autokraft's owner, Brian Angliss.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1982, Brian Angliss was running Autokraft, a Cobra restoration shop, parts supplier and replica manufacturer.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] To further such pursuits, he acquired some of the tooling from Thames Ditton and created the MKIV; the car had US-spec 5 mph (8.0 km/h) bumpers, a US-regulations compliant motor, and a larger interior with modern switchgear.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] About 480 cars were produced in his factory at Brooklands.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] He also produced a lightweight model which was more in tune with the original Cobra spirit, though it could not be exported to the US owing to federal regulations.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Early cars were sold as the Autokraft MKIV, but eventually Angliss acquired the rights to use the AC name.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Derek Hurlock had been strongly protective of the name, but Angliss' high standards of craftsmanship won him over.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] When the Hurlock family finally sold up in 1986 Angliss fully acquired the AC trademark rights and set up a new AC company as a joint venture with Ford, who had also recently bought Aston Martin.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] A big conflict followed over the future direction for AC, but Angliss eventually won his independence as well as Ford's continuing and essential cooperation as an engine and parts supplier.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Also interested in aircraft, Angliss restored a Hawker Hurricane XIIB at Brooklands as well as acquiring two ex–Indian Air Force Hawker Tempest IIs as future projects.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The Hurricane was registered as G-HURR and was destroyed in a fatal accident at the Shoreham air show in 2007.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Angliss looked for a new car to complement and perhaps replace the MKIV.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] At the 1993 London Motor Show, he introduced a new vehicle that he named the AC Ace.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] It was a modern automobile with a stainless steel chassis and an aluminium body, but was expensive to develop and build.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The costs hit Angliss hard and he sold his large motor bike collection, vintage Bentley and other assets to try to make ends meet.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The receivers were called in by 1996 after approximately 50 "new" Aces had been built.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In March 1996, largely due to the cost of developing the new Ace, Angliss' company went into receivership and was eventually sold to South African businessman Alan Lubinsky in December 1996, who continued car production in Weybridge, Surrey, under the name of AC Car Group Ltd.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Both the Cobra Mk IV and the Ace were made, and soon a 'CRS' version of the Mk IV was announced with a carbon fibre body shell, a 212 S/C version with Lotus twin-turbo V8 power, as well as the AC Superblower with a supercharger Ford V8.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Two Aceca coupes (enclosed version of the Ace) were also made.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In August 2002, AC Motor Holdings Ltd. was incorporated in Malta.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 2003, Carroll Shelby International and AC Motor Holdings Ltd. announced the production of an authentic Shelby/AC Cobra, with the production vehicle arriving at dealers in July 2004.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Initial models included Shelby AC 427 S/C Cobra and Shelby AC 289 FIA Cobra, which were branded as the CSX 1000 and CSX 7500 Series, respectively.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In February 2004, the first handcrafted aluminium body shell was built at Frimley works.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 2004, a new manufacturing plant was opened in Malta and production of the carbon-fibre-bodied AC MkV began.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Due to problems with the factory building, production ceased in 2007.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In August 2008, Acedes Holdings LLC was incorporated in St Kitts.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 2008, AC announced a joint venture with Brooklands Motor Company (the spiritual successor of Autokraft) in Weybridge, Surrey, and confirmed plans for the continuation of the traditional AC designed tubular chassis and aluminium-bodied models.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In April 2009, a joint venture in Germany was announced to manufacture the new AC MKVI.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] AC Automotive, based in Straubenhardt, Germany, built AC cars under the original name from 2010 to mid-2023.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Cars were sold in Germany, France and England, with sales in Luxembourg, Holland, Lichtenstein, Switzerland, and Belgium slated for the future.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Pricing for the standard ACGT model starts at £104,400 before options.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The AC Automotive company went into liquidation on 24 July 2023.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Following a supply deal with GM, the AC MKVI had a novel spaceframe chassis, 6.2-litre V8 engine and 6-speed manual transmission, and new Corvette brakes, retaining the original shape in lightweight composite material with the moulds taken from an original AC MKIII body.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The car went into series production in July 2012 after two years of intense prototyping and development.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 2010, AC announced a joint venture with the USA-based company Iconic which resulted in the design of the ultimate "Cobra": the "Iconic AC Roadster".
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] At the Geneva Motor Show in 2012, AC Cars showed three different models: the AC MK VI, AC MK II Classic, and AC 378 GT Zagato.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 2020, AC Cars announced that they would be building a zero-emission version of the Cobra called the Series 1 Electric.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] Fifty-eight of these electric sports cars will be built alongside a 2.3-litre petrol version called the AC Cobra 140 Charter Edition.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 2022, the new corporate structure began the production of 663 new AC Cobra models, with a slightly modified structure to adapt it to modern safety and technology requirements and obtain the European road homologation certificate.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] In 1949, AC Cars produced four trains, each consisting three power cars and four coaches, for the Southend Pier Railway in Essex.
[src:bristol-cars/ac-cars] The company also ventured briefly into the railway rolling stock business, building five four-wheel railbuses for British Rail in 1958.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The AJS company has a motorcycle racing legacy and held 117 motorcycle world records related to events such as the Isle of Man TT races.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Joe Stevens, father of Harry, George, Albert John (‘Jack’), and Joe Stevens Junior, was an engineer who owned the Stevens Screw Company Ltd, in Wednesfield, near Wolverhampton.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Stevens had a reputation for quality engineering before the company built its first motorcycle in 1897, using a Mitchell single-cylinder four-stroke imported from the US.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Before long, Stevens began making engines, starting off with a better-built version of the Mitchell but the family soon developed their own designs, including parallel-twins and V-twins, which were sold as proprietary engines to other manufacturers, including Werner, Wolf and Clyno.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1909, after a Wearwell motorcycle fitted with a Stevens side-valve single-cylinder engine won a trophy for a 24-hour non-stop run in 1909, Jack Stevens decided to contest the Tourist Trophy in the Isle of Man.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] A new company, A J Stevens & Co (AJS), was founded, with premises in Retreat Street, Wolverhampton, to manufacture motorcycles and the first model appeared at the Motor Cycle Show in 1910.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Its engine, a two-speed 298 cc side-valve, was made to come within the 300 cc limit for Junior machines in the 1911 Isle of Man TT races and was slightly larger than the 292 cc used for the proprietary engines.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Jack Stevens came 16th on AJS's official entry, one place behind private owner J.D.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Albert John Stevens lent his initials to the company, but it was a family concern.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1922 for example, Harry Stevens acted as managing director, George Stevens as commercial manager, Joe Stevens Junior managing the experimental section and Jack Stevens as production manager.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] AJS did not contest the 1912 TT as it was busy satisfying the demand for its products, but was 10th in the 1913 Junior.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] With the Junior limit raised to 350 cc for 1914, the AJS motorcycle had grown to 349 cc, with four-speed gears and chain final drive.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] AJS achieved their first TT victory in the Junior 1914 Isle of Man TT race that year through Eric Williams, whilst also taking second, third, fourth and sixth place.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The old Screw Company's facilities could not cope with the demand and with the company reconstituted as *A.J.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Stevens and Company (1914) Ltd*, AJS moved to a new factory built around Graiseley House, in the Blakenhall district, a short distance south of the Retreat Street premises, which were relegated to the being the company's office and repair department.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The 349 cc machine (known as the 2+3⁄4 hp) was most in demand but the company also produced an 800 cc (6 hp) V-twin.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] This kept AJS busy until Ministry of Munitions restrictions were lifted in January 1919.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] When production of the 350 resumed in 1920, it was much improved.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The side-valve engine was replaced by a new overhead-valve design that produced 10 bhp.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] It also had internal expanding brakes and chain primary drive.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Cyril Williams won the first post war 1920 Isle of Man TT Junior race on his 350, even though he had to push the motorcycle home for almost four miles (mostly downhill) after a breakdown.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] AJS took the first four places in the 1921 Isle of Man TT, and Howard R Davies bettered his second place in the Junior by winning the Senior on the same 350 cc AJS.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] This was the first time a 350 had won the 500 cc Senior TT race.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1922 Manxman Tom Sheard won the Junior on an AJS, with G Grinton, also on an AJS, taking second.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The 1922 machine was a classic design that would become famous as the ‘Big Port’ on account of its large-diameter exhaust port and pipe (initially 15⁄8 inches, but changed in successive years).
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The OHV 350 would be the mainstay of the company's racing efforts until 1927 and in production form (first offered to the public in 1923), was also AJS's most popular sports motorcycle throughout the 1920s.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] At this time, the company produced a comprehensive range of other models ranging from 250 to 1,000 cc.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] These were generally given a model number, plus letter to denote the year of manufacture (for example, B meant 1924, F 1925, G 1926).
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Several of these were intended to pull one of the 12 AJS sidecars also on offer, including sports, touring and commercial models.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] By 1927, it had become clear that push-rod overhead-valve designs were becoming dated in racing, so AJS introduced two new chain-driven overhead-camshaft racing models, the 349 cc K7 and the 498 cc K10.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Jimmy Simpson rode a 350 to third place in the Junior TT and won races in Europe but in 1928 AJS used the overhead-valve engine in the TT.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1929 there were again two machines with an overhead cam, this time the 349 cc M7 and the 498 cc M10.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Wal Handley came second in the 1929 Junior TT for AJS.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The following year Jimmie Guthrie won the 1930 Lightweight TT on a 250 cc AJS.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1931, the AJS S3 V-twin was released, a 496 cc transverse V-twin tourer with shaft *primary* drive and alloy cylinder heads.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] It had been expensive to develop and was slow to sell.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Even though it held 117 world records, the AJS company was now in financial trouble.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The 1935 film *No Limit* was set at the Isle of Man TT.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The film starred George Formby as an aspiring racer who travels to the Isle of Man with his modified and streamlined 1928 *"Rainbow"* motorcycle, which he has christened a *Shuttleworth Snap,* in order to compete at the races.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In the film fictitious motorcycle companies were used, and the *Shuttleworth Snap* was in fact a 1928 AJS H5.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Although best known for their motorcycles the company made a few experimental cars with Meadows engines in 1923 but decided not to go into full production.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] AJS had manufactured car bodies for Clyno, but in 1929 Clyno went under.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] AJS returned to car making in 1929 with the Nine powered by a 1018 cc side-valve Coventry-Climax engine producing 24 bhp (18 kW) and driving through a three-speed gearbox.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The cars were quite expensive at £210 for the two-seater and £320 for the fabric bodied saloon.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The company also started making buses and coaches.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The first model was the Pilot with a Meadows engine.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] This was followed by the Commodore with a Coventry Climax L6 engine and finally by the Admiral.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] After BSA failed to obtain control, the motorcycle assets were bought by the Collier brothers London company Matchless and the car manufacturer Crossley Motors.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Crossley incorporated some improvements such as a four-speed gearbox and using parts acquired from AJS built about 300 cars between December 1931 and May 1932.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Assembly took place in the Stockport factory used by Willys Overland Crossley.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Motorcycle production moved to Plumstead in London.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] A 1½-litre model was planned, but failed to materialize except to appear on the Willys-Overland-Crossley stand at the 1932 London Motor Show.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1938, AJS became part of a group called Associated Motorcycles, formed by the Colliers as a management company for its various interests.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] After this Matchless and AJS generally shared models using different badging, although the AJS name was used for several unique racers.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The site of the Wolverhampton factory, now a supermarket, is marked by a sculpture, *The Lone Rider*, designed by Steve Field and carved by Robert Bowers, assisted by Michael Scheuermann.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The Stevens brothers tried again and started a new company as **Stevens Brothers (Wolverhampton) Ltd** to make 3-wheel delivery vans.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] (They could not call them AJS, as that name belonged to the Colliers.) These used a 588 cc single-cylinder engine driving the rear wheels through a 3-speed gearbox and chain drive.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] It was improved in 1935 with shaft drive and uprated to 8 cwt.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1934 they also produced a new range of motorcycles under the Stevens name.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] These were made until 1938 after which the company continued until 1956 as a general engineering business.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] AJS designer Harry Stevens was a keen amateur 'ham' radio operator since before World War I.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1922, following the launch of Britain's first radio stations and the formation of the BBC he convinced the rest of the AJS board that radio receivers had a big future.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The first radios made by AJS Wireless and Scientific Instruments were launched in 1923, all high quality models aimed at the top end of the market.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The most expensive cost £75, which was substantially more than many AJS motorcycles, although prices soon fell.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Initial sales were good and by 1925, there were 10 models ranging from under £14 in a simple wooden case to over £50 with a finely veneered console cabinet.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Radio production was increased and moved to a factory in Stewart Street.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] However, radio technology had advanced rapidly and AJS was forced to offer new designs in order to compete.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The company's reliance on battery power held them back at a time when rivals were turning to mains power and AJS was forced to adopt cheaper mass-production techniques.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1928, the company decided to give up radio manufacture and sold the factory and remaining components to the Symphony Gramophone and Radio Company.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Under AMC the AJS badge may have been put on the "bread and butter" Matchless motorcycles, but the Colliers were mindful of the AJS racing heritage, and used the name on some innovative racing machinery.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] These racing bikes kept the AJS name alive.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1935, at the Olympia Show, an air-cooled SOHC AJS 50° V4 was shown, a fully equipped road going version, which did not make it into production.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1936 Harold Daniell rode a supercharged race version in the Isle of Man Senior TT, but despite its high top speed, it lacked acceleration.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1939, a water-cooled and supercharged version of the 495 cc AJS V4 was built to compete against the supercharged BMWs then dominating racing.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1939 the dry sump V4 was the first bike to lap the Ulster Grand Prix course at over 100 mph (160 km/h).
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] It weighed 405 lb (184 kg). and its top speed was 135 mph (217 km/h).
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] At the end of the 1940s and start of the 1950s, the AJS Porcupine, a 500 cc forward-facing parallel twin, and the AJS 7R (32 bhp, 350 cc OHC single) were being raced alongside their AMC stablemates the Matchless G50 (effectively a 500 cc 7R) and by 1951, the Matchless G45 (a 500 cc vertical twin).
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The AJS Porcupine had been designed for supercharging, before the rules changed banning supercharged racing motorcycles, but even so, Les Graham won the 1949 World Championship on an unsupercharged AJS E90 500 cc Porcupine.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1951 AJS development engineer Ike Hatch developed a 75.5 mm bore × 78 mm stroke, three-valve-head version of the 7R making 36 bhp (27 kW).
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] It was called the AJS 7R3, and was Ike's response to the Italian multi-cylinder racers.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] They did well enough in their first year, not as well the second.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] For 1954 Jack Williams, the works team manager, developed the bike further, lowering the engine in the frame, and making some tuning changes that gave 40 bhp (30 kW) @ 7800 rpm.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] It immediately won the first two rounds of the World Championship and took first at the Isle of Man TT.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] These were factory specials, but one has survived, and a second has been reconstructed from spares.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] AMC withdrew from the world of works and one-off road racing at the end of the 1954, with the death of Ike Hatch, and in the face of fierce competition from the other European bikes.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] After this AJS made a production version of the standard two-valve AJS 7R, for privateers.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1954 Norton was also moved to the Plumstead works.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] With the G15 line, AMC had built on the merits of the G12 but there were numerous changes to frame, forks, swinging arm, primary chaincase, transmission, cycle parts and lubrication system.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The P11 was the last line of bikes with bonds to AMC.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] It used a modified G85CS frame but there were stronger forks, completely new cycle parts (making some was rather costly), altered lubrication and modified primary chaincases, to mention a few.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The G15 series was offered as 3 brands: Matchless G15 comprising G15Mk2, G15CS and G15CSR; AJS Model 33 comprising M33Mk2, M33CS and M33CSR; and last not least Norton N15CS (no Norton-branded roadster made as it would compete against the Atlas).
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The G15 series was produced from 1963 to 1969.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] They were initially for export only, but by 1965 these models were available in UK and Europe too.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Associated Motorcycles and the AJS name eventually ended up with Norton-Villiers in 1966.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In late 1968 the Plumstead works at Burrage Grove, where engines from the Wolverhampton plant and frames from the Manchester plant were assembled into complete machines, were presented with a Greater London Council compulsory purchase order.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The Plumstead works closed in July 1969.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] It is believed that production of the G15 series was halted late in 1968 (model year 1969) with unsold samples on offer through 1969.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The AJS Model 33 was the last AJS badged four-stroke produced.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] From 1962 Cotton motorcycles were the main customer for 250 Starmaker engines.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The 250 Starmaker engines were used in the Cotton Cobra scrambler and the Telstar Racer.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Cotton therefore was very involved in the development of the Starmaker engine..
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Peter Inchely formerly from Ariel and BSA was involved with the 250 Road Race project.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Inchley rode a Bultaco-based 6-speed, 250 Villiers Starmaker-powered special to 3rd place in the 1966 Lightweight TT.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Several pre production AJS 250 Racers were built and raced but the project came to halt in 1967 after an unsuccessful second TT attempt.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The scrambles project continued with considerable success.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] From 1966 to 1968, Villiers developed the "Stormer" Motocross motorcycle.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1968 Malcolm Davis won the British 250 Championship on a pre Stormer, Y4 scrambler.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In late 1967, a special project was undertaken with the Stormer.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Four bikes were built at Marston Road, all equipped with spark arrestors on the end of the tailpipe and with a rudimentary lighting system.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Three of them had 250 cc engines and were badged as AJS machines.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The fourth one had the "360" engine (actually only 334 cc) and was badged as a Matchless.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] This bike was probably the last one built with a Matchless badge and the only two-stroke Matchless.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The four bikes were taken on by members of the Royal Air Force motor Sports Association and entered in the 1968 International Six-Days Trial.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The two-stroke AJSs had been built in Wolverhampton, at the Villiers factory but in 1970 the UK government provided a special subsidy that enabled AJS to open a new factory on Walworth Industrial Estate in Andover, where they assembled Stormer off-road motorcycles.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The competition department was located next to the famous race track at Thruxton, Andover.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] AJS scramblers were produced from 1968 until 1974 in 250, 370 and 410 guises.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In 1969 The 370 (Y5) was added and the name changed to Stormer.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] A little known about motorcycle was the 37AT Trials bike which was partially built by Cotton Motorcycles using some AJS parts and Villiers's 37A engine.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] By 1974, Norton Villiers was having financial trouble, and the rights to manufacture the Stormer under the AJS banner were purchased.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] In September 1974 the business was moved to Goodworth Clatford near Andover.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Initially selling spare parts for existing motorcycles, the business expanded to produce complete motorcycles still using the Starmaker-based engines under the FB-AJS name.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The Starmaker/Stormer four-speed engine was becoming outdated and could not compete with the new arrivals from manufacturers such as Husqvarna, CZ and later, scrambles bikes from Maico, Suzuki, Honda, Kawasaki and Yamaha.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] From 1974 Stormer-based scrambles and trail bikes were sold from modified AJS stock.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] During the early 1980s off-road and trail bike with Austrian Rotax engines of 250 cc, 410 cc and 495 cc were produced.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Rather they purchase from companies in China.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] The bikes have AJS logos and other custom detailing features.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] Their 124cc range are built around the Jianshe JS125 frame and engine.
[src:bristol-cars/ajs] These are first imported from China then distributed through their UK dealer network and exported to Germany, Portugal, Cyprus, Czech Republic, Japan and S.
[src:bristol-cars/ats-euromaster] At its peak, the company had around 525 service centres, this was sometime in the nineties and since then it has continued to close non profitable service centres with a view to reopen at more strategic locations.
[src:bristol-cars/ats-euromaster] Euromaster made a structured wind down of its UK ATS Euromaster operation and ceased operations on 01 May 2026 after 60 years.
[src:bristol-cars/ats-euromaster] ATS operates a number of centres equipped for both car and van MOTs and servicing.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] In 1986, General Motors decided to sell their Bedford heavy-duty truck division to David J.B.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] Brown, who was the founder of Artix Limited, while they re-formed the Bedford light truck division into IBC Vehicles.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] The now-called AWD Trucks were mostly made for the export market, on which they were very popular, but in Britain, they were only bought by the construction industry and the military.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] At that time Brown opened a new firm called *Multidrive Vehicles* that built 8x6 versions of the AWD TK and AWD TL, mostly for the military and special services.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] By that time the AWD company had achieved £3 billion of exports and gained 4 Queen's Awards to Industry, with an annual turnover of £400 million.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] Brown sold the Multidrive Vehicles company to Caterpillar.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] Brown then became a design consultant for the Cat 7 Series ADT.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] The Bedford trucks that were built by Multidrive Vehicles, were modernized, re-skinned, and were re-badged to Caterpillar vehicles.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] These Caterpillar trucks were exported to many countries and were also used in the Gulf War, in Bosnia, Kosovo, and in other countries.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] The company re-entered the British market in 2001, and also started exports to South Africa that same year.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] In 2003 the company started producing a whole new range of military vehicles, but the production of the older trucks did not stop.
[src:bristol-cars/awd-trucks] With the death of Brown in 2006, the company was bought by Dr Qu Li.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Bristol was always a low-volume manufacturer; the most recent published official production figures were for 1982, which stated that 104 cars were produced in that year.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The company also had only one sales showroom, on the corner of Kensington High Street and Holland Road in London.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The company suspended manufacturing in March 2011, when administrators were appointed, 22 staff were made redundant at the factory in Filton, Bristol and subsequently the company was dissolved.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] In April 2011, a new company was formed by the administrator to sell the original assets to Kamkorp.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The new company was liquidated in 2020 in order to pay creditors.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The British aircraft industry suffered a dramatic loss of orders and great financial difficulties following the Armistice of 1918.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Stanley White, managing director of the Bristol Aeroplane Company from 1911 to 1954, was determined not to suffer the same difficulties a second time.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The company now employed 70,000 and he knew he must plan for the time when the wartime demand for Bristol aircraft and aircraft engines would suddenly end.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The company began working with AFN Ltd, manufacturers of Frazer Nash cars and British importer of BMWs before the war, on plans for a joint venture in automotive manufacture.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] As early as 1941, a number of papers were written or commissioned by Sir George S.M.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] White, Sir Stanley's son, proposing a post-war car manufacturing division.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] It was decided to purchase an existing manufacturer for this purpose.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Alvis, Aston Martin, Lagonda, ERA and Lea-Francis were considered.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] In May 1945, a chance discussion took place between D.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Aldington, a director of AFN Ltd, then serving as an inspector for the wartime Ministry of Aircraft Production (MAP), and Eric Storey, an assistant of George White at the Bristol Aeroplane Company.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] By July 1945, the Bristol Aeroplane Company had created a car division and bought a controlling stake in AFN.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] A factory was established at Bristol Filton Airport, where Bristol Aeroplane already had substantial premises.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Aldington and his two brothers had marketed the Frazer Nash BMW before the war, and proposed to build an updated version after demobilisation.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] This seemed the perfect match for the aeroplane company's own ambitions to manufacture a high quality sports car.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] With the support of the War Reparations Board, H.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Aldington travelled to Munich and purchased the rights to manufacture three BMW models and the 328 engine.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] George White and Reginald Verdon-Smith of the aeroplane company joined the new Frazer Nash Board, but in January 1947, soon after the first cars had been produced, differences between the Aldingtons and Bristol led to the resale of Frazer Nash.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The Bristol car division became an independent entity.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Bristol Cars was sold after its parent joined with other British aircraft companies in 1960 to create the British Aircraft Corporation (BAC), which later became part of British Aerospace.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The car division originally merged with Bristol Siddeley Engines, and was marked for closure, but was bought in September 1960 by George White, the chairman and effective founder.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] White retained the direction of the company, but sold a forty per cent shareholding to Tony Crook, a leading Bristol agent.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] In September 1969, only a month before the unveiling of the new Bristol 411 at the Earl's Court Motor Show, Sir George S.M.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] White suffered a serious accident in his Bristol 410.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The car was only superficially damaged, but he suffered severe trauma.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] As time passed it became clear that he would never regain his health sufficiently to return to full-time work.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] To safeguard the future of his workforce, he decided in 1973 to sell his majority shareholding to Crook.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] As the ties with the White family were severed, British Aerospace requested the company to move its factory from Filton Aerodrome and it found new premises in nearby Patchway.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The showroom on Kensington High Street became the head office, with Crook shuttling between the two in Bristol's light aircraft.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Under Crook's direction the company produced at least six types, the names of which were largely borrowed from Bristol's aeronautical past: the Beaufighter, Blenheim, Britannia and Brigand.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] In February 1997, Crook, then aged 77, sold a fifty per cent holding in Bristol Cars to Toby Silverton, with an option to take full control within four years.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Silverton, then son-in-law of Joe Lewis of the Tavistock Group and son of Arthur Silverton of Overfinch, joined the board with his father.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Crook and Toby Silverton produced the Speedster, Bullet, Blenheim and 411 Series 6, though 2002 saw the transfer of Bristol Cars fully into the ownership of Silverton and the Tavistock Group, with Silverton in the chair and Crook remaining as managing director.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Together they developed a V10 engined two-seater named after the first Sir George White's First World War two-seater aircraft, the Bristol Fighter.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Crook finally relinquished his connection with Bristol Cars in August 2007.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] On 3 March 2011 it was announced that Bristol Cars had gone into administration, with the loss of 22 jobs when the factory at Filton, Bristol was shut down.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] On 21 April 2011 another new company was formed to sell the assets of the former dissolved company; that company was purchased by Kamkorp, which also owned Frazer-Nash Research, a technology manufacturer of electric power systems.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] During this era, the company focused on restoring and selling all models of the marque while a new model was being developed.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] In 2015 Bristol Cars announced the development of a new model codenamed "Project Pinnacle".
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Initial reports indicated it would be a petrol-electric hybrid with a petrol engine from BMW.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] However a later media report and a May 2015 press release, indicated that the car would have non-hybrid V8 power.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The car, a two-seater roadster, made its first public appearance, slightly camouflaged, at the Goodwood Festival of Speed in June 2016.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] In July, the car was shown undisguised, technical details were announced, and its name given as the Bristol Bullet.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] However, subsequently there was no further news about the car's homologation, and many members of the sales and marketing team soon left the company.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The Bullet was said to be powered by a normally aspirated 370 bhp (280 kW; 380 PS) 4.8-litre BMW N62 V8 engine (sharing the same drivetrain and chassis as the most recent Morgan Aero 8) driving the rear wheels, had a body of carbon fibre, weighed 1130 kg, and would cost £95,000.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The planned production run was said to be limited to 70 cars to commemorate the marque's 70th anniversary.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] On 5 March 2020 it was reported that Bristol cars had been officially wound up in order to pay creditors, with court-ordered liquidation under way.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The Bristol Owners Club working together with the Bristol Owners and Drivers Association and the Bristol Owners Heritage Trust is reported to be actively engaged in order to preserve the heritage and associated spares for the marque.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] In 2021, intellectual property rights to Bristol Cars were registered by Bristol Fighter Limited, a subsidiary of Bristol Manufacturing Limited, owned by Essex based investor and property developer Jason Wharton, with revocation of 297 defunct trademarks.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Wharton plans to transform the company into a "leading British electric vehicle company" by 2026, the brand's 80th anniversary.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The new Bristol Cars would firstly launch "remastered" versions of historic cars with modernised mechanicals on a built to order basis.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] It was also reported that the new company will subsequently revive the Buccaneer nameplate for an all new electric vehicle.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Shortly after this announcement, however, controversy erupted between Wharton and Bristol's insolvency practitioner Frost Group.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The practitioner stated that Wharton had in fact not purchased any intellectual property rights, but had merely purchased certain tooling and spares at the auction of the company's assets.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Despite this controversy, plans to revive the brand continued and Wharton announced in 2024 that Bristol would be revived as a contemporary coachbuilder by 2026.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] HJ Aldington, a director of the Bristol Aeroplane Company affiliated AFN (BMW's pre-war concessionaire in the UK), used his British Army connections to visit the bombed BMW factory in Munich several times post-war.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] In 1945 he took plans for BMW cars back to Britain, and BMW chief engineer, Dr.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Its first car was the Bristol 400, prototyped in 1946 and introduced at the 1947 Geneva Motor Show.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Derived from immediately pre-WW2 BMW products (thanks to a connection to BMW through Frazer Nash), the chassis was based on the BMW 326, the engine on the 328, and the body on the 327.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Even a variation on the famous double-kidney BMW grille was retained.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Bristol, however, did a thorough examination of the car's handling and ended up with performance "only matched by outright purpose-built competition cars".
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Seven hundred of the Bristol 400 were built, 17 of which received "handsome" drophead bodywork from Pininfarina.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] In 1949, the 400 was joined by the five-place 401.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Bodied by Touring, it was aerodynamically sleeker, accelerated better, and had higher top speed.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] It was joined by the drophead 402, of which just 24 examples were built.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The 403 followed in 1953, which featured improved brakes, gearbox, dampers, heater, and engine (a detuned racing motor, in fact).
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Bristol would use this same engine in the 450, entered at Le Mans in 1953; it broke its experimental crankshaft, but despite being less than aerodynamically ideal proved fully five seconds a lap quicker than the competition.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Bristol withdrew from racing two years later.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Along with the 403 was the 404, on a shorter wheelbase, with a more powerful engine and styling reminiscent of the 450.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The 404 introduced a concealed front wing-mounted spare wheel and battery.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] It was built to extremely exacting standards, and the price reflected it; this, plus newly introduced "punitive taxation", meant only 40 were produced.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The 405, which entered production in 1954, was much more successful, not least for being Bristol's only four-door.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] It remained in production until 1958, with 297 saloons and 43 drophead coupés produced in all.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Bristol debuted the 406 in 1958, and it remained in production until 1961.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The 406's replacement, the 407, was powered by a 5.2-litre V8 provided by Chrysler of Canada.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] It was followed in 1963 by the 408, with drastic restyling as well as improved suspension.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Many buyers preferred the crisp steering and gearbox of the earlier six-cylinder cars.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The 410, introduced in 1966, was a return to the high-performance touring tradition, offering the same top speed as the 409, and superior acceleration, with the same powerplant.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] It also saw Bristol become a private company and marked a return to quality to the exclusion of output: no more than three cars a week were to be made.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] In 1969, the Bristol 411 appeared, with a new 6.2-litre Chrysler V8 (still rebuilt and modified by Bristol, as before) delivering higher top speed and even better acceleration.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] Until 1961 all Bristol cars used Bristol-built derivatives of the BMW M328 2-litre six-cylinder engine.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] These engines also powered a number of sports and racing cars, including all post-war Frazer Nashes (apart from a few prototypes), some ACs, some Lotus and Cooper racing cars, and several others.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] In 1961, with the launch of the Bristol 407, the company switched to larger Chrysler V8 engines, which were more powerful than Bristol's own, BMW derived 2.25-litre 6 cylinder engine.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] The Chrysler V8s could be bought off the shelf from Canadian Chrysler without the startup costs of Bristol's own 3.65-litre all alloy 6 then in development.
[src:bristol-cars/bristol-cars] All post-1961 Bristols, including the later Blenheim and Fighter models, used Chrysler engines.
